'''Clouding of consciousness''', also known as '''brain fog''' or '''mental fog''',<ref name="Schildkrout">{{cite book |author=Barbara Schildkrout |title= Unmasking Psychological Symptoms |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |location=|year=2011 |pages=183–184 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xIL8VHItTp4C&lpg=PA184&dq=%22clouding%20of%20consciousness%22%20%22mental%20fog%22&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=%22clouding%20of%20consciousness%22%20%22mental%20fog%22&f=false |isbn=9780470639078 }}</ref><ref name="Basa">{{cite book |author= M. Basavanna |title=Dictionary of psychology |publisher=Allied Publishers |year=2000 |pages=65 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=sXgbdsaGDKYC&lpg=PA65&dq=%22clouding%20of%20consciousness%22%20%22mental%20fog%22&pg=PA65#v=onepage&q=%22clouding%20of%20consciousness%22%20%22mental%20fog%22&f=false |isbn= 8177640305}}</ref> is a term used in medicine denoting an abnormality in the regulation of the overall level of [[consciousness]] that is mild and less severe than a [[delirium]].<ref name="Plum5">{{cite book |title=Plum and Posner's diagnosis of stupor and coma |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2007 |pages=5–6 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=eDcWsh3FCFQC&lpg=PT20&dq=%22overall%20level%20of%20cortical%20function%22&pg=PT20#v=onepage&q=%22overall%20level%20of%20cortical%20function%22&f=false |isbn=9780199886531}}</ref> The sufferer experiences a [[subjectivity|subjective]] sensation of mental clouding described as feeling "[[fog]]gy".<ref name="Grassi82">{{cite book |author1=Augusto Caraceni |author2=Luigi Grassi |title=Delirium: Acute Confusional States in Palliative Medicine |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2011 |pages=82 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=qiUfHyoC_zUC&lpg=PA82&dq=foggy%20subjective&pg=PA81#v=snippet&q=foggy%20clouding&f=false |isbn=9780199572052}}</ref>

